> ##### Variant Rule: Large Player Characters
> 5th Edition was built under the assumption that player characters would be exclusively be playing Medium or Small races. Choosing to play a race that is Large size comes with both pros and cons, allowing you to 
> 
> ***Areas of Effect.*** 
>
> ***Carrying Capacity.*** You have double the carrying capacity (PHB p. 176).
>
> ***Consumables.*** You require four times as much food and water per day (DMG p. 111).
>
> ***Cover.*** It should be harder for a Large creature to find cover (PHB p. 196). The DM will adjudicate this, but roughly speaking where a Medium creature would find total cover, a Large creature might only receive three-quarters cover; where a Medium creature finds three-quarters cover, a Large creature might only receive half cover; and where a Medium creature finds half cover, a Large creature might find none.
>
> ***Equipment.*** Armor, clothing, and other items made for your size costs four times as much as the equivalent made for Medium sized creatures and weighs twice as much. Large containers such as backpacks also have four times the carrying capacity. You can ignore the increased costs when determining starting equipment, and most magic items will resize to fit you character.
>
> ***Reach.*** 
>
> ***Unarmed Strikes.*** You deal 1d4 + your Strength modifier damage with unarmed strikes.
> 
> ***Weapons.*** Large-sized creatures can use Large-sized weapons (DMG p. 278). However, this rule was intended for determining the threat of monster opponents, not player characters. Instead use the variant rule for Oversized weapons (page ###). When using Medium-sized weapons, use the following rules for weapon properties: 
> - You struggle with Light weapons and have disadvantage on attack rolls with them.
> - One handed weapons without the Versatile trait are treated as Light weapons for the purposes of qualifying for two-weapon fighting.
> - Weapons with the Versatile trait deal the damage given in parenthesis even if wielded in only one hand.

